svg:text.svg:tspan: A model of the atom that says that the atom has a small, central positively-charged
nucleus with negatively-charged electrons moving around the nucleus, and that
most of the atom is empty space. The nucleus is made up of protons and neutrons.
The centre of an atom, containing protons and neutrons.
A conductor with resistance that is constant at a constant temperature.
A circuit in which every component is connected separately
to the positive and negative ends of the battery.
When waves are incident on a boundary, some are reflected and some are transmitted.
The process in which other scientists check the results and
explanations of an investigation before they are published.
The time taken for one full cycle of a wave to be completed.
A magnetic material that always has its own magnetic field around it.
A change where you don’t end up with a new substance — it’s the same substance as before,
just in a different form. (A change of state is a physical change.)
A natural object in space which orbits a star.
The driving force that pushes electric charge around a circuit,
measured in volts (V). Also known as pd or voltage.
The rate of transferring energy (or doing work). Normally measured in watts (W).
When all the data is close to the mean.
A statement that can be tested and is based on a hypothesis.
The force per unit area exerted on a surface.
The point where rays hitting the lens parallel to the axis appear to have come from.
The point where rays hitting the lens parallel to the axis all meet.
A subatomic particle with a relative charge of +1.
The earliest stage in the life cycle of a star. Protostars are formed when
the force of gravity causes clouds of dust and gas to pull together.
A measure of the risk of harm to your body due to exposure to radiation.
The random process of a radioactive substance giving
out radiation from the nuclei of its atoms.
A substance that spontaneously gives out radiation from the nuclei of its atoms.
A treatment of cancer that uses ionising radiation (such as gamma rays and X-rays)
A type of electromagnetic wave mainly used for radio and TV signals.
